Date: Mon, 3 Aug 1998 18:28:04 -0400 (EDT)
From: Michael T Wong <miwong@hsc.vcu.edu>

Normally, I don't reply to these, but this poor fellow seems really
desperate.
The obvious conditions (HIV, hepatitis viruses) have been ruled out. A
negative Lyme [disease serology does not rule out _Borrelia burgdorferii_,
and may need more specific testing (Lyme Western blot, or when highly
suspected, PCR from specific body fluid such as synovial (joint) or CSF).
_Histoplasma capsulatum_ is by far and away the most likely endemic fungus
associated with bat guano; the literature is ripe with cases involving
spelunckers, and can cause a myriad of symptoms including pericarditis (can
cause positional chest pain), musculo-skeletal findings, and in rare, but
not unheard of cases, CNS disease (more likely in the immunocompromised
populations, but can occur in purportedly immunocompetent persons).
Cryptococcal disease is not very common with bat-guano; it is more a
feature of exposure to pigeon droppings or bird coops. It can result in
disseminated forms in persons with otherwise intact immunologic systems,
but seizures can occur (usually in association with a meningitis and
changes in level-of-consciousness).
The exposures to mountain biking leaves leptospirosis in the differential,
although low white cell counts are usually (but not exclusively) seen in
this infection, and it can mimic other spirochetal diseases in presentation.
Ticks can transmit a number of rickettsial organisms, but on the East Coast
(did I get the affected person's geographic home correct), these are
usually Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever. Likewise, seizures may be associated,
but at this stage, the infected person is usually moribund. In addition to
RMSF, ticks can transmit a non-Lyme borrelial species that causes
"relapsing fever"--this isn't supposed to cause significant focal
neurologic events. If there is a missed tick, and one is still present on
his body, "tick bite fever" can actually result in numerous neurologic
complaints with or without fever and myalgias (muscle aches), and is a
result of circulating tick antigens.
Given the food habits (raw meats), I would also evaluate for
macro-parasites that can lead to CNS involvement such as cystercercosis,
sparagonomiasis (_Diphylobothium latum_ or fish tapeworm from poorly
prepared sushi), and if he has eaten "drunk crabs" in the Philippines, then
paragonomiasis. Most of these macro-parasites cross tissue plains and will
cause an eosinophilia ("allergic" response white count), and usually have
some GI symptoms.
It is unlikely that this represents human ehrlichiosis as the white count
is low with this disease.
And, are we sure these are seizures the person is experiencing, and not
rigors (shaking chills), which may be associated with a number of other
processes including too-numerous-to-count bacterial processes (rat bite
fever- he's in NYC, bacterial endocarditis, etc).
I'll leave the toxicology stuff to our toxicology colleagues.
--
Michael Wong, MD
Infectious Diseases
Medical College of Virginia Hospitals
Virginia Commonwealth University
e-mail: miwong@hsc.vcu.edu
